<DOC><DOCNO> AP880324-0074 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0808EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Rebels     03-24 0180</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Sudan-Rebels,0185</SECOND><HEAD>Government Shells Rebel Positions In Southern Sudan</HEAD><DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government shelled positions held byguerrillas in southern Sudan, killing 295 rebels and regainingcontrol of a town, an army statement said.   Government troops moving toward rebel-held Nasir town in thesouthern upper Nile region found the bodies of 250 rebels killedfrom shelling, according to the Wednesday statement.   It said that at the outskirts of Nasir, the soldiers killed 45other rebels. Two government troops were killed and eight woundedbefore the army took over full control of the area, it said.   It did not say when the operation took place.   In other clashes, the statement said soldiers killed 19 rebelsin an army attack Saturday on the rebels' Bekwy camp, near Mundaritown in the Equatoria region.   In another operation near the border with Zaire, government andrebel troops fought Saturday and a number of rebels were killed andwounded. The statement had no casualty numbers.   The rebels began their insurrection in 1983 and are demandingmore autonomy and administrative and economic reforms.</TEXT></DOC>